an Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Brazilian people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:Catholic socialists]]\n[[Category:Collars of the Order of Isabella the Catholic]]\n[[Category:Collars of the Order of the Aztec Eagle]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Royal Norwegian Order of Merit]]\n[[Category:Honorary Knights Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chamber of Deputies (Brazil) from S\u00e3o Paulo]]\n[[Category:People from Pernambuco]]\n[[Category:Politicians with physical disabilities]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Workers' Party (Brazil)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Great Cross of the National Order of Scientific Merit (Brazil)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Aeronautical Merit (Brazil)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Boyaca]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Liberty (Ukraine)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Military Merit (Brazil)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Naval Merit (Brazil)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Prince Yaroslav the Wise]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Companions of O. R. Tambo]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Southern Cross]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Four Freedoms Award]]\n[[Category:People convicted of bribery]]\n[[Category:Brazilian politicians convicted of corruption]]\n[[Category:Heads of regimes who were later imprisoned]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Equatorial Star]]\n", "name_user": "2804:18:480c:dfcd:23a2:83b9:d3e5:8a55", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luiz_In%C3%A1cio_Lula_da_Silva"}
{"title_page": "Charlotte Parker", "text_new": "\n\n\n'''Charlotte Parker (n\u00e9e Charlotte Adler, n\u00e9e Charlotte Faye Greenberg)''' (born in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]]) is the co-founder of Parker Communications, a media company that includes Parker Public Relations. She has guided the public images of over 200 celebrities, politicians, executives and corporations. As an expert media analyst and image consultant Parker has appeared on [[CNN]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0312/13/cst.15.html|title=CNN.com|last=|first=|date=|website=transcripts.cnn.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[MSNBC]], [[Court TV]], and the [[E-Channel]] and been written about in ''[[Spy (magazine)|Spy Magazine]]'',<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xa7j5ofHW0EC&pg=PA64&lpg=PA64&dq=charlotte+parker+time+magazine+arnold+schwarzenegger+cannes&source=bl&ots=UwcAXetokP&sig=ACfU3U1EcQHGOgeFPdVezqUbQZgB7JOhoA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjhlZSdoqzjAhUkB50JHUh4CloQ6AEwC3oECAgQAQ%20-%20v=onepage&q=charlotte%20parker%20time%20magazine%20arnold%20schwarzenegger%20cannes&f=false|title=Spy Magazine, Naked Schwarzenegger: Inside Arnold\u2019s Propaganda Machine|last=Fleming|first=Charles|date=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> ''[[Columbia Journalism Review|The Columbia Journalism Review]]'',<sup>[1]</sup> ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' and ''[[Los Angeles Times Magazine|The Los Angeles Times Magazine]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1995-03-22-fi-45765-story.html|title=Los Angeles Times|last=|first=|date=1995-03-22|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nThe daughter of [[Holocaust]] survivors Herman and Sara Adler, Parker was raised in [[Cleveland, Ohio]].  She graduated from New York City's [[Stern College for Women]] and attended graduate school at [[Hebrew University]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afhu.org/2017/09/04/charlotte-parker/|title=Charlotte Parker|website=American Friends of Hebrew University|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref> in [[Jerusalem]] and [[CCNY]], where she studied English Literature, creative writing and poetry.\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating college Parker worked for ''Penthouse Magazine'' as assistant to the production director, John Evans. While there she came up with the idea of a magazine about marijuana and its lifestyle, and started working on it at night. This morphed into the popular counterculture publication ''Head Magazine'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abebooks.com/magazines-periodicals/Head-October-1976-GREENBERG-Charlotte-Faye/8406259952/bd|title=Head; October, 1976 by GREENBERG, Charlotte Faye - Editor: Alshar Co., New York Stapled Wrappers, Vol 1, No 7. - Antiquarius Booksellers|website=www.abebooks.com|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref> for which she was the editor and publisher, as Charlotte Faye Greenberg, for four years. During that time the magazine became known for its articles, photography and interviews with important figures including [[Timothy Leary]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/annotatedbibliog00hororich|title=An annotated bibliography of Timothy Leary|last=|first=|last2=|first2=|last3=|first3=|last4=|first4=|date=1988|publisher=Hamden, Conn. : Archon Books|others=Timothy Leary Archive|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> and [[Peter Tosh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://marleyarkives.wordpress.com/2012/09/13/rare-peter-tosh-interview-head-magazine-1977/|title=Rare Peter Tosh Interview, Head Magazine (1977)|last=|first=|date=2012-09-13|website=Midnight Raver|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As Charlotte Faye Greenberg, she served on the advisory board of The National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws (NORML),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalfamilies.org/legalization/norml1978.html|title=NORML 1978 - Drug Legalization|website=www.nationalfamilies.org|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref> and was a guest of honor at the 1977 International Hallucinogenic Mushroom Conference along with R. Gordon Wasson and Albert Hofmann.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mushroomjohn.org/worldconferenceonshrooms1977a.htm|title=World Conference on Hallucinogenic Mushrooms|last=|first=|date=|website=www.google.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref> ''The New York Times'' quoted her in 1976 as saying that marijuana use was \u201cone of the fastest growing recreational activities in the country.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/07/29/archives/advertising-big-bates-campaign-taking-off.html|title=Advertising|last=Dougherty|first=Philip H.|date=1976-07-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 1980 Parker moved to Los Angeles and was appointed Director of Public Relations for the Academy of Television Arts and Sciences. From there she worked for [[Lee Solters]] at Solters, Roskin, Friedman Public Relations where she was the publicist for television programs including the ABC comedy sketch series, ''[[Fridays (TV series)|Fridays]]'', which launched the careers of [[Larry David]], [[Michael Richards]], and [[Melanie Chartoff]] among others. She then went to Rogers & Cowan Public Relations, where she worked with [[Warren Cowan]], [[Dale Olson]] and [[Ronni Chasen]] in the film division.\n\nIn 1985 Parker started her own public relations agency, Parker Public Relations. She may be best known for her work with [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5vxwV6uFcC0C&pg=PA25&lpg=PA25&dq=charlotte+parker+publicist&source=bl&ots=U6NhKJa8ki&sig=ACfU3U3g_yruEsEUmXiPowFSZcsjXLFg4g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjFqOyBrKzjAhXTKs0KHV_KDwsQ6AEwDnoECAkQAQ%20-%20v=onepage&q=charlotte%20parker%20publicist&f=false|title=The People's Machine: Arnold Schwarzenegger and the Rise of Blockbuster Democracy|last=Mathews|first=Joe|date=2006-08-08|publisher=PublicAffairs|isbn=9781586482725}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2006-sep-17-op-mathews17-story.html|title=Arnold still loves the camera|date=2006-09-17|website=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/books/2013/06/28/fantastic-life-decent-book/2467447/|title='Fantastic' life, decent book|website=USA TODAY|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref> whom she personally represented for 14 years, beginning with ''[[Conan the Destroyer]]'' (Parker also represented the film). In the Schwarzenegger biography ''Fantastic'', author [[Laurence Leamer]] called her \"a key player in his rise to stardom.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p_lPLwK8r0UC&pg=PA206&lpg=PA206&dq=charlotte+parker+terminator&source=bl&ots=m989OysUoy&sig=ACfU3U2E2kSH2uQVydRXj8QEeCS_4NWm9Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjAh_qUm6zjAhVKVs0KHfbjC_QQ6AEwCnoECAgQAQ%20-%20v=onepage&q=charlotte%20parker%20terminator&f=false|title=Fantastic: The Life of Arnold Schwarzenegger|last=Leamer|first=Laurence|date=2006-05-30|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=9781429906364}}</ref>\n\nParker launched the publicity campaigns of director [[James Cameron]] and producer [[Gale Anne Hurd]]. She represented director [[John Frankenheimer]], producers John Davis, and [[Arnold Kopelson]], [[Jesse Ventura]], Shannon Lee, the [[Audrey Hepburn]] Children's Fund, World Wrestling Federation, World Championship Wrestling and the films ''[[The Terminator]]'', ''[[Aliens (film)|Aliens]]'', ''[[Total Recall (1990 film)|Total Recall]]'', and the animated film ''[[The Swan Princess]]'', among others. She\u00a0 was a key figure in the corporate launch of [[Planet Hollywood Las Vegas|Planet Hollywood]] and created the launch campaign for [[Original New York Seltzer]]. Among those she represented is fitness legend [[Joe Weider]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/entertainment-us-usa-weider-idUSBRE92M0ED20130323|title=Bodybuilding icon Joe Weider dies in Los Angeles at 93|last=|first=|date=2013-03-23|work=Reuters|access-date=}}</ref> She also served on the Board of the [[Bruce Lee]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20060807005581/en/Bruce-Lees-Family-Opens-Offices-Hong-Kong|title=Bruce Lee's Family Opens Offices in Hong Kong and Beijing|last=|first=|date=2006-08-07|website=www.businesswire.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freewebs.com/brucelee-fan/bruceleefoundation.htm|title=Bruce Lee Foundation|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nParker co-created the E-Channel original film ''Murder at the [[Cannes Film Festival]]''<ref>{{Citation|last=|first=|title=Murder at the Cannes Film Festival (TV Movie 2000) - IMDb|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0245301/fullcredits|volume=|pages=|access-date=}}</ref> and was Executive Producer of the entertainment television news program ''The Industry News'' ''and Marketplace''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1995-03-22-fi-45765-story.html|title=COMPANY TOWN ANNEX|last=|first=|date=1995-03-22|website=Los Angeles Times|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Parker hosted her own radio show on [[Los Angeles]] station [[KRLA]], called ''Get What You Want with Charlotte Parker''.\n\n==Personal life==\nParker is married to Joel Parker, who is her partner at Parker Communications, They have a daughter, Ruth Parker, and reside in [[Encino, California]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parker, Charlotte}}\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Austrian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American radio personalities]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People from Encino, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Stern College for Women alumni]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Cleveland]]\n[[Category:Hebrew University of Jerusalem alumni]]\n[[Category:City College of New York alumni]]\n[[Category:American public relations people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesswomen]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Vienna]]\n[[Category:American magazine founders]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n\n'''Charlotte Parker (nee Charlotte Adler, nee Charlotte Faye Greenberg)''' (born in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]]) is the co-founder of Parker Communications, a media company that includes Parker Public Relations. She has guided the public images of over 200 celebrities, politicians, executives and corporations. As an expert media analyst and image consultant Parker has appeared on [[CNN]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0312/13/cst.15.html|title=CNN.com|last=|first=|date=|website=transcripts.cnn.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[MSNBC]], [[Court TV]], and the [[E-Channel]] and been written about in ''[[Spy (magazine)|Spy Magazine]]'',<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xa7j5ofHW0EC&pg=PA64&lpg=PA64&dq=charlotte+parker+time+magazine+arnold+schwarzenegger+cannes&source=bl&ots=UwcAXetokP&sig=ACfU3U1EcQHGOgeFPdVezqUbQZgB7JOhoA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjhlZSdoqzjAhUkB50JHUh4CloQ6AEwC3oECAgQAQ%20-%20v=onepage&q=charlotte%20parker%20time%20magazine%20arnold%20schwarzenegger%20cannes&f=false|title=Spy Magazine, Naked Schwarzenegger: Inside Arnold\u2019s Propaganda Machine|last=Fleming|first=Charles|date=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> ''[[Columbia Journalism Review|The Columbia Journalism Review]]'',<sup>[1]</sup> ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' and ''[[Los Angeles Times Magazine|The Los Angeles Times Magazine]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1995-03-22-fi-45765-story.html|title=Los Angeles Times|last=|first=|date=1995-03-22|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nThe daughter of [[Holocaust]] survivors Herman and Sara Adler, Parker was raised in [[Cleveland, Ohio]].  She graduated from New York City\u2019s [[Stern College for Women]] and attended graduate school at [[Hebrew University]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afhu.org/2017/09/04/charlotte-parker/|title=Charlotte Parker|website=American Friends of Hebrew University|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref> in [[Jerusalem]] and [[CCNY]], where she studied English Literature, creative writing and poetry.\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating college Parker worked for ''Penthouse Magazine'' as assistant to the production director, John Evans. While there she came up with the idea of a magazine about marijuana and its lifestyle, and started working on it at night. This morphed into the popular counterculture publication ''Head Magazine'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abebooks.com/magazines-periodicals/Head-October-1976-GREENBERG-Charlotte-Faye/8406259952/bd|title=Head; October, 1976 by GREENBERG, Charlotte Faye - Editor: Alshar Co., New York Stapled Wrappers, Vol 1, No 7. - Antiquarius Booksellers|website=www.abebooks.com|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref> for which she was the editor and publisher, as Charlotte Faye Greenberg, for four years. During that time the magazine became known for its articles, photography and interviews with important figures including [[Timothy Leary]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/annotatedbibliog00hororich|title=An annotated bibliography of Timothy Leary|last=|first=|last2=|first2=|last3=|first3=|last4=|first4=|date=1988|publisher=Hamden, Conn. : Archon Books|others=Timothy Leary Archive|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> and [[Peter Tosh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://marleyarkives.wordpress.com/2012/09/13/rare-peter-tosh-interview-head-magazine-1977/|title=Rare Peter Tosh Interview, Head Magazine (1977)|last=|first=|date=2012-09-13|website=Midnight Raver|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As Charlotte Faye Greenberg, she served on the advisory board of The National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws (NORML),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalfamilies.org/legalization/norml1978.html|title=NORML 1978 - Drug Legalization|website=www.nationalfamilies.org|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref> and was a guest of honor at the 1977 International Hallucinogenic Mushroom Conference along with R. Gordon Wasson and Albert Hofmann.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mushroomjohn.org/worldconferenceonshrooms1977a.htm|title=World Conference on Hallucinogenic Mushrooms|last=|first=|date=|website=www.google.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref> ''The New York Times'' quoted her in 1976 as saying that marijuana use was \u201cone of the fastest growing recreational activities in the country.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/07/29/archives/advertising-big-bates-campaign-taking-off.html|title=Advertising|last=Dougherty|first=Philip H.|date=1976-07-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 1980 Parker moved to Los Angeles and was appointed Director of Public Relations for the Academy of Television Arts and Sciences. From there she worked for [[Lee Solters]] at Solters, Roskin, Friedman Public Relations where she was the publicist for television programs including the ABC comedy sketch series, ''[[Fridays (TV series)|Fridays]]'', which launched the careers of [[Larry David]], [[Michael Richards]], and [[Melanie Chartoff]] among others. She then went to Rogers & Cowan Public Relations, where she worked with [[Warren Cowan]], [[Dale Olson]] and [[Ronni Chasen]] in the film division.\n\nIn 1985 Parker started her own public relations agency, Parker Public Relations. She may be best known for her work with [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5vxwV6uFcC0C&pg=PA25&lpg=PA25&dq=charlotte+parker+publicist&source=bl&ots=U6NhKJa8ki&sig=ACfU3U3g_yruEsEUmXiPowFSZcsjXLFg4g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjFqOyBrKzjAhXTKs0KHV_KDwsQ6AEwDnoECAkQAQ%20-%20v=onepage&q=charlotte%20parker%20publicist&f=false|title=The People's Machine: Arnold Schwarzenegger and the Rise of Blockbuster Democracy|last=Mathews|first=Joe|date=2006-08-08|publisher=PublicAffairs|isbn=9781586482725}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2006-sep-17-op-mathews17-story.html|title=Arnold still loves the camera|date=2006-09-17|website=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/books/2013/06/28/fantastic-life-decent-book/2467447/|title='Fantastic' life, decent book|website=USA TODAY|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref> whom she personally represented for 14 years, beginning with ''[[Conan the Destroyer]]'' (Parker also represented the film). In the Schwarzenegger biography ''Fantastic'', author [[Laurence Leamer]] called her \"a key player in his rise to stardom.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p_lPLwK8r0UC&pg=PA206&lpg=PA206&dq=charlotte+parker+terminator&source=bl&ots=m989OysUoy&sig=ACfU3U2E2kSH2uQVydRXj8QEeCS_4NWm9Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjAh_qUm6zjAhVKVs0KHfbjC_QQ6AEwCnoECAgQAQ%20-%20v=onepage&q=charlotte%20parker%20terminator&f=false|title=Fantastic: The Life of Arnold Schwarzenegger|last=Leamer|first=Laurence|date=2006-05-30|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=9781429906364}}</ref>\n\nParker launched the publicity campaigns of director [[James Cameron]] and producer [[Gale Anne Hurd]]. She represented director [[John Frankenheimer]], producers John Davis, and [[Arnold Kopelson]], [[Jesse Ventura]], Shannon Lee, the [[Audrey Hepburn]] Children\u2019s Fund, World Wrestling Federation, World Championship Wrestling and the films ''[[The Terminator]]'', ''[[Aliens (film)|Aliens]]'', ''[[Total Recall (1990 film)|Total Recall]]'', and the animated film ''[[The Swan Princess]]'', among others. She\u00a0 was a key figure in the corporate launch of [[Planet Hollywood Las Vegas|Planet Hollywood]] and created the launch campaign for [[Original New York Seltzer]]. Among those she represented is fitness legend [[Joe Weider]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/entertainment-us-usa-weider-idUSBRE92M0ED20130323|title=Bodybuilding icon Joe Weider dies in Los Angeles at 93|last=|first=|date=2013-03-23|work=Reuters|access-date=}}</ref> She also served on the Board of the [[Bruce Lee]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20060807005581/en/Bruce-Lees-Family-Opens-Offices-Hong-Kong|title=Bruce Lee's Family Opens Offices in Hong Kong and Beijing|last=|first=|date=2006-08-07|website=www.businesswire.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freewebs.com/brucelee-fan/bruceleefoundation.htm|title=Bruce Lee Foundation|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nParker co-created the E-Channel original film ''Murder at the [[Cannes Film Festival]]''<ref>{{Citation|last=|first=|title=Murder at the Cannes Film Festival (TV Movie 2000) - IMDb|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0245301/fullcredits|volume=|pages=|access-date=}}</ref> and was Executive Producer of the entertainment television news program ''The Industry News'' ''and Marketplace''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1995-03-22-fi-45765-story.html|title=COMPANY TOWN ANNEX|last=|first=|date=1995-03-22|website=Los Angeles Times|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Parker hosted her own radio show on [[Los Angeles]] station [[KRLA]], called ''Get What You Want with Charlotte Parker''.\n\n==Personal life==\nParker is married to Joel Parker, who is her partner at Parker Communications, They have a daughter, Ruth Parker, and reside in [[Encino, California]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parker, Charlotte}}\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Austrian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American radio personalities]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People from Encino, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Stern College for Women alumni]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Cleveland]]\n[[Category:Hebrew University of Jerusalem alumni]]\n[[Category:City College of New York alumni]]\n[[Category:American public relations people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesswomen]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Vienna]]\n[[Category:American magazine founders]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo fixing,typo(s) fixed: (nee \u2192 (n\u00e9e (2), \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charlotte_Parker"}
{"title_page": "Clara (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2017 romantic science fiction film directed by Akash Sherman}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Clara\n| image          = Clara poster.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = Akash Sherman\n| producer       = Ari Lantos\n| writer         = \n{{Plainlist|\n*Akash Sherman\n*James Ewasiuk\n}}\n| starring       = \n{{Plainlist|\n*[[Patrick J. Adams]]\n*[[Troian Bellisario]]\n}}\n| music          = Jonathan Kawchuk\n| cinematography = Nick Haight\n| editing        = Matt Lyon\n| production companies = Serendipity Point Films ''in association with'' Distant Horizon\n| distributor    = D Films\n| released       = {{film date|2018|09|10|[[2018 Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 105 minutes\n| country        = Canada, [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n}}\n'''''Clara''''' is a Canadian-British [[science fiction film]] and the second feature film directed by Akash Sherman. The film stars husband and wife actors [[Patrick J. Adams]] and [[Troian Bellisario]], playing astrophysicist Isaac and itinerant artist Clara, who fall in love while searching for signs of intelligent life in the universe.\n\n==Plot==\nDr. Isaac Bruno holds a postdoctoral research fellowship in astrophysics at (fictional) Ontario University, in [[Toronto]]. His goal of finding signs of intelligent life in the universe has become an obsession, linked to an unspecified trauma in his personal life two years earlier. He has become increasingly antagonistic towards his students and has taken to misappropriating time on ground-based telescopes in Chile, intended for a colleague's research. His department head suspends him, denying him any access to the school's research facilities.\n\nThe [[Transiting Exoplanet Survey Satellite|TESS]] orbiting telescope is launched, providing enormous amounts of data that is shared with the world, in a community effort to analyze and find possible life on [[exoplanet]]s. Isaac posts flyers looking for an unpaid research assistant, offering nothing but room and board. His only response is from Clara, an uneducated artist who has lived a [[Bohemianism|Bohemian lifestyle]]. Clara has her own secrets, seen taking some type of medicine for an unspecified issue.\n\nIsaac focuses on results from [[Red dwarf|M dwarf]] stars, believing it to be a niche that no one else will bother with. When Clara finds a promising exoplanet, Isaac sneaks into the university in the night and lies to the telescope operators in Chile, claiming to have permission from his friend Charlie, to get more data on the planet.\n\nCharlie is furious, but also intrigued by the data results. He advises Isaac to contact Rebecca, Isaac's ex-wife, who holds an endowed chair at [[California Institute of Technology|Caltech]]. Clara convinces Isaac to contact Rebecca, despite his reluctance. The upheaval in their lives is finally revealed, when Rebecca tells Isaac that finding life will not bring back their dead baby son. She gets him some time on the [[W. M. Keck Observatory|Keck]] telescope. This results in proving that they have found a [[Planetary habitability|habitable planet candidate]].\n\nClara is falling in love with Isaac, but he has become jaded about love or anything else that can not be scientifically proven. She kisses him, then abruptly backs off when he starts to respond. When Charlie's wife has a baby, Isaac pontificates on how a minuscule change took his own son, and could equally change the entire universe. Clara reminds him that those same minuscule changes did result in his son existing at all. This leads to them finally becoming a couple. \n\nWhen they learn that someone else discovered \u201ctheir\u201d planet a week before them, Isaac becomes despondent. He soon decides to focus on finding direct evidence of life, rather than just a potentially habitable planet. In his obsession, he is blind to Clara's declining health, until Charlie chastises him. Isaac tells Clara it is time for him to stop his search, but she makes him ignore the data and focus on his inner connection to the universe. He is surprised when it works, but rejects it and her. She grabs her bag to leave - and collapses.\n\nAt the hospital, it is revealed that Clara has an autoimmune disease that is causing the complete breakdown of every organ and muscle in her body. The doctors are shocked that she can even walk or talk, and confirm she will soon be dead. Isaac stays at her bedside for her last few days. Moments before she dies, she tells him he is going to \u201csee it\u201d.\n\nA fresh batch of TESS data is released, and Isaac does \u201csee it\u201d - proof of a seemingly artificial object in coincident orbit with an exoplanet. He takes his findings to Charlie, who introduces him to Dr. Rickman, head of the TESS project. Two years later, at a press conference at the [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory|JPL]], Dr. Rickman, Rebecca and Charlie explain that the data gathered now conclusively proves the existence of the artificial object, orbiting a star 200 light years distant, in turn proving the existence of intelligent alien life. Isaac is not in his assigned seat on the panel, choosing instead to spend time reminiscing about Clara.\n\nA few months later, Rebecca summons Isaac to the [[Search for extraterrestrial intelligence|SETI]] laboratory. She reveals that the aliens have sent a message&mdash;\u201cIsaac Bruno\u201d. He is present when the next message arrives &ndash; an audio file of a [[Bob Dylan]] song that he and Clara often listened to together. The film ends with Isaac smiling through his tears.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Patrick J. Adams]] as Dr. Isaac Bruno \n* [[Troian Bellisario]] as Clara\n* [[Ennis Esmer]] as Dr. Charlie Durant \n* [[Kristen Hager]] as Dr. Rebecca Jenkins \n* [[R. H. Thomson]] as Dr. Rickman\n* [[Jennifer Dale]] as Astrophysics Department Head\n\n==Themes and genre==\nA story about \"space and love\",<ref name=\"Slotek\">{{cite web |last1=Slotek |first1=Jim (interviewer) |title=Original-Cin Review/Q&A: Clara Filmmaker Shoots for the Stars (and Mostly Reaches \u2018Em, Too) |url=https://www.original-cin.ca/posts/2018/11/27/original-cin-reviewqampa-clara-filmmaker-shoots-for-the-stars-and-mostly-reaches-em-too |website=Original-Cin.ca |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Sherman titled the film ''Clara'' because the word means \"clear\" and \"bright,\" like a star: \"it was about this search for life among the stars.\"<ref name=\"Billings\">{{cite journal |last1=Billings |first1=Lee (interviewer) |title=''Clara'' Is a Story of Exoplanets, Existential Longing\u2014and Real Science |journal=[[Scientific American]] |date=11 October 2018 |url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/clara-is-a-story-of-exoplanets-existential-longing-mdash-and-real-science1/ |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Sherman did not consider the film [[romantic film|romantic]], but anticipated it would be marketed that way \"because the lead actors are married in real life\"; it is a love story to the extent that there is \"a binding bond between two characters\" who are \"just two people connecting for a bit.\"<ref name=\"Slotek\" />\n\n==Production==\n===Background and writing===\nSherman studied at [[Ryerson University|Ryerson]]'s film school for one year, where one day, at 19, he became determined to write a story, shutting himself in his dormitory room for seven hours.<ref name=\"Slotek\" /> \n\nFriends Sherman made at Ryerson worked with him on his debut, ''The Rocket List'', \"made on no budget ... on a four-day road trip with a camera,\"<ref name=\"Malyk\">{{cite journal |last1=Malyk |first1=Lauren |title=TIFF \u201918: The winning formula behind Akash Sherman\u2019s Clara |journal=[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]] |date=10 September 2018 |url=https://playbackonline.ca/2018/09/10/clara-a-sci-fi-stepping-stone/ |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> as well as on ''Clara''.<ref name=\"Slotek\" /> Together with James Ewasiuk, a \"close collaborator\" who co-wrote ''The Rocket List'' with him, Sherman did four months of research on \"the Kepler telescope and transits and things like that.\"<ref name=\"Slotek\" />\n\nBoth romantic leads contributed ideas. Adams was involved with the project from an early stage, giving feedback to Sherman on his script, on character in particular, which the director began revising in earnest at age 20 and finished two years later.<ref name=\"Knight\" /> Bellisario provided \"a similar depth for her character,\" and suggested a different ending for the film, a note which Sherman accepted: \"I had a different ending in mind, which I don't want to share because it's not as good.\"<ref name=\"Knight\" /> It was Bellisario who brought up [[quantum entanglement]] for one of the earlier drafts.<ref name=\"Slotek\" /> \n\n====Scientific accuracy====\nThe detection method and the specialized telescopes depicted in ''Clara'' are not fictional. The [[Transiting Exoplanet Survey Satellite|TESS]] space telescope is a 2018 upgrade of the [[Kepler Telescope]] which was used to discover over 4000 [[exoplanets]] iin the decade since 2009.<ref name=\"Shanahan\">{{cite web |last1=Shanahan |first1=Don |title=Clara Grounds Solemnity and Sweetness Into Complicated Love Within Science Fiction |url=https://25yearslatersite.com/2019/09/19/clara-grounds-solemnity-and-sweetness-into-complicated-love-within-science-fiction/ |website=25YearsLaterSite.com |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Sherman gave a talk on the science behind the film at the Astronomy On Tap event in Toronto on 17 August 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"The Science of CLARA\" - Akash Sherman at Astronomy On Tap, Toronto HD |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2nFL-thbPP0 |website=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Sherman relied on three scientific advisors, Canadian astrophysicists John Moores and Doug Welch,<ref name=\"Billings\" /> at [[York University|York]] and [[McMaster University|McMaster]] universities respectively, and Barth Netterfeld of the [[University of Toronto]]:  \"Almost everything was vetted by them. It,s so vetted, in fact, that the climactic discovery in the movie... turned out to be an original idea\", later published by the [[American Astronomical Society]].<ref name=\"Slotek\" />\n\n===Financing===\n''Clara'' was produced by Serendipity Point in association with [[London]]-based Distant Horizon, with the support of [[Telefilm Canada]], the Ontario Media Development Corporation, the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]], and [[Bell Media]]'s [[The Movie Network|TMN]].<ref name=\"Pinto\">{{cite journal |last1=Pinto |first1=Jordan |title=Production begins on Serendipity Point\u2019s Clara |journal=[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]] |date=7 March 2017 |url=http://playbackonline.ca/2017/03/07/production-begins-on-serendipity-points-clara/ |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] took place in [[Toronto]] during the month of March in 2017.<ref name=\"Pinto\" /> Leads Adams and Bellisario were married a little earlier,<ref name=\"Knight\">{{cite news |last1=Knight |first1=Chris |title=Akash Sherman looks to the cosmos for Clara, his second feature film |url=https://nationalpost.com/entertainment/movies/akash-sherman-looks-to-the-cosmos-for-clara-his-second-feature-film |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=[[The National Post]] |date=November 28, 2018}}</ref> and spent a large portion of their [[honeymoon]] working on the film.<ref name=\"Collider\">{{cite web |title=Clara: Patrick J. Adams, Ari Lantos, and Director Akash Sherman on Their Grounded Sci-Fi Film [Collider interview] |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TFHtf7vTBmg |website=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=17 April 2020 |format=video}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nComposer Jonathan Kawchuk wrote a \"soft score\", complimenting musical selections by [[Bob Dylan]].<ref name=\"Shanahan\" />\n\n==Release==\n''Clara'' premiered at the [[2018 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref>[https://nowtoronto.com/movies/tiff-2018-canadian-films-rob-stewart/ \"TIFF 2018: Rob Stewart, Denys Arcand, Jennifer Baichwal films among Canadian titles\"]. ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]'', 1 August 2018.</ref> This was followed by a [[limited theatrical release]].<ref name=\"Shanahan\" />\n\n===Distribution===\nD Films was responsible for ''Clara's'' Canadian theatrical distribution, while the CBC holds the television broadcast rights, and TMN holds the [[pay TV]] rights.<ref name=\"Pinto\" />\n\n===Home media and streaming===\n''Clara'' is available on DVD<ref>{{cite web |title=Clara (DVD) - Walmart.com |url=https://www.pinterest.com/pin/112027109497857701/ |website=[[Pinterest]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> and Blu-ray.<ref>{{cite web |title=Clara |url=https://www.blu-ray.com/Clara/1139480/ |website=Blu-ray.com |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe film is available on [[video on demand]] platforms<ref name=\"Shanahan\" /> such as [[Amazon Prime]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Clara |url=https://www.amazon.com/Clara-Patrick-J-Adams/dp/B07RJ1T87C |website=[[Amazon.com]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception== \n===Critical response===\n''Clara'' has a critic review score of 48% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 23 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |title=Clara (2018) |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/clara_2018/ |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which uses a weighted score, the film has a score of 43 out of 100 based on six reviews.<ref>{{cite web |title=Clara |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/clara |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAssigning the film 2 stars at [[RogerEbert.com]], Peter Sobczynski called the film \"peculiar and largely unsatisfying\" despite the ambitions displayed by Akash Sherman: \"the result is a weird muddle that's both too silly to be taken seriously and too staid to completely go off the beaten path.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sobczynski |first1=Peter |title=Clara |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/clara-2019 |website=RogerEbert.com |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Toronto critic Norman Wilner, writing for ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]'', though conceding the film has its moments, feels that the story stops where it ought to have begun.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilner |first1=Norman |title=Review: Toronto-set Clara stops just where it ought to begin |url=https://nowtoronto.com/movies/reviews/review-clara-akash-sherman/ |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=[[Now (newspaper)|Now]] |date=November 28, 2018}}</ref> Tara Thorne finds that ''Clara'' has \"outsized ideas that dominate and weaken the film beneath it\", lacking in humour but featuring too much \"data talk\", though it finally gains traction in the last twenty minutes, a \"big reveal\" that pays off but also sacrifices genuine emotions for \"dutifully plotted emotional beats.\" Having said all this, Thorne calls Sherman an \"assured director who clearly has big plans.\"<ref name=\"Thorne\">{{cite news |last1=Thorne |first1=Tara |title=Film review: Clara |url=https://www.thecoast.ca/halifax/film-review-clara/Content?oid=19372258 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=The Coast |date=November 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nUnlike Thorne, Don Shanahan finds the real life science as an \"interwoven backdrop\" provides a \"narrative boon for the science fiction of ''Clara''.\" Its \"sense of intelligence intertwines with the unpredictability found in the amorous reverberations of the human heart\", a combination which makes for an \"intimate and daring film experience\", a \"rare treat\" to have \"two narrative genres combined with smarts and affection.\"<ref name=\"Shanahan\" /> Writing for ''[[Exclaim!]]'', Alex Hudson finds the science more intriguing than what he calls the film's philosophical musings, but, despite its flaws, it works as a mood piece: \"the colours are muted, the score is appropriately etherial, and it effectively captures Isaac's depression as he searches for meaning in his broken life. It gets under the skin even when it doesn't stimulate the mind.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hudson |first1=Alex |title='Clara' Is an Ambitious Hunt for the Meaning of Life |journal=[[Exclaim!]] |date=December 3, 2018 |url=http://exclaim.ca/film/article/tiff_review_clara_is_an_ambitious_hunt_for_the_meaning_of_life-directed_by_akash_sherman |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nGiving the film a B rating, Jim Slotek calls ''Clara'' a \"solidly written\" that \"shows a sure-handed storytelling career that's just getting started\", benefiting from NASA\u2013provided photos and effects \"cannily\" used to give it \"the look of a much higher budgeted movie\".<ref name=\"Slotek\" />\n\n===Scientific response and influence===\nThe film's trailer, due both to \"lush\" visual effects and \"teasing science-savvy plot points\" attracted a lot of attention on social media from astronomers,<ref name=\"Billings\" /> and led to a mention in a science journal for Sherman's \"innovative thoughts on how to search for life in other star systems.\"<ref name=\"Slotek\" />\n\nIsaac and Clara's use of publicly available data from [[NASA]]'s TESS has \"surprisingly robust real-world roots\" in a \"''Clara''-inspired academic paper\" written by the scientific advisors, published in ''[[Research Notes of the American Astronomical Society]]''.<ref name=\"Billings\" /> The article, titled \"Simulating Transits at the L1 Point\", shares credit with Sherman. \"They credited me as a scientist. I'm published! So, that's really cool.\"<ref name=\"Slotek\" />\n\n===Accolades===\n====Award====\n*[[Austin Film Festival]], 2018 \u2022 Jury Award for a Narrative Feature (Akash Sherman and James Ewasiuk)<ref>{{cite web |title=2018 Winners |url=https://austinfilmfestival.com/blog/festival-and-conference/2018-winners/ |website=[[Austin Film Festival]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Nominations====\n;2018\n*[[Directors Guild of Canada]] Discovery Award;<ref>{{cite web |title=Discovery Award Long List 2018 |url=https://www.dgc.ca/en/national/news/discovery-award-long-list-2018/ |website=dcg.ca |publisher=[[Directors Guild of Canada]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> [[shortlist]]ed (1 of 4)<ref>{{cite web |title=Directors Guild presents: Visionaries at TIFF |url=https://www.dgc.ca/visionaries/visionaries/ |website=dcg.ca |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> \n*[[Vancouver Film Critics Circle]] One to Watch Award and Best Best Actress in a Canadian Film<ref>{{cite web |title=Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award Nominations |url=https://theawardspsychic.blogspot.com/2018/12/vancouver-film-critics-circle-award.html |website=The Awards Psychic |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n;2019\n*[[Golden Trailer Awards]] Best Foreign Poster<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hipes |first1=Patrick |title=Golden Trailer Awards Nominations: \u2018A Star Is Born\u2019, Netflix Lead Way |journal=Deadline |date=9 May 2019 |url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/golden-trailer-awards-nominees-2019-nominations-list-netflix-a-star-is-born-1202610742/ |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.facebook.com/CLARATheFilm/ Official page] on [[Facebook]]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7eIbm4cfA8M Official trailer] on [[YouTube]]\n* {{IMDb title|6613878}}\n\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:2010s science fiction films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Canadian science fiction films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2017 romantic science fiction film directed by Akash Sherman}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Clara\n| image          = Clara poster.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = Akash Sherman\n| producer       = Ari Lantos\n| writer         = \n{{Plainlist|\n*Akash Sherman\n*James Ewasiuk\n}}\n| starring       = \n{{Plainlist|\n*[[Patrick J. Adams]]\n*[[Troian Bellisario]]\n}}\n| music          = Jonathan Kawchuk\n| cinematography = Nick Haight\n| editing        = Matt Lyon\n| production companies = Serendipity Point Films ''in association with'' Distant Horizon\n| distributor    = D Films\n| released       = {{film date|2018|09|10|[[2018 Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 105 minutes\n| country        = Canada, [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n}}\n'''''Clara''''' is a Canadian-British [[science fiction film]] and the second feature film directed by Akash Sherman. The film stars husband and wife actors [[Patrick J. Adams]] and [[Troian Bellisario]], playing astrophysicist Isaac and itinerant artist Clara, who fall in love while searching for signs of intelligent life in the universe.\n\n==Plot==\nDr. Isaac Bruno holds a postdoctoral research fellowship in astrophysics at (fictional) Ontario University, in [[Toronto]]. His goal of finding signs of intelligent life in the universe has become an obsession, linked to an unspecified trauma in his personal life two years earlier. He has become increasingly antagonistic towards his students and has taken to misappropriating time on ground-based telescopes in Chile, intended for a colleague's research. His department head suspends him, denying him any access to the school's research facilities.\n\nThe [[Transiting Exoplanet Survey Satellite|TESS]] orbiting telescope is launched, providing enormous amounts of data that is shared with the world, in a community effort to analyze and find possible life on [[exoplanet]]s. Isaac posts flyers looking for an unpaid research assistant, offering nothing but room and board. His only response is from Clara, an uneducated artist who has lived a [[Bohemianism|Bohemian lifestyle]]. Clara has her own secrets, seen taking some type of medicine for an unspecified issue.\n\nIsaac focuses on results from [[Red dwarf|M dwarf]] stars, believing it to be a niche that no one else will bother with. When Clara finds a promising exoplanet, Isaac sneaks into the university in the night and lies to the telescope operators in Chile, claiming to have permission from his friend Charlie, to get more data on the planet.\n\nCharlie is furious, but also intrigued by the data results. He advises Isaac to contact Rebecca, Isaac's ex-wife, who holds an endowed chair at [[California Institute of Technology|Caltech]]. Clara convinces Isaac to contact Rebecca, despite his reluctance. The upheaval in their lives is finally revealed, when Rebecca tells Isaac that finding life will not bring back their dead baby son. She gets him some time on the [[W. M. Keck Observatory|Keck]] telescope. This results in proving that they have found a [[Planetary habitability|habitable planet candidate]].\n\nClara is falling in love with Isaac, but he has become jaded about love or anything else that can not be scientifically proven. She kisses him, then abruptly backs off when he starts to respond. When Charlie's wife has a baby, Isaac pontificates on how a minuscule change took his own son, and could equally change the entire universe. Clara reminds him that those same minuscule changes did result in his son existing at all. This leads to them finally becoming a couple. \n\nWhen they learn that someone else discovered \u201ctheir\u201d planet a week before them, Isaac becomes despondent. He soon decides to focus on finding direct evidence of life, rather than just a potentially habitable planet. In his obsession, he is blind to Clara's declining health, until Charlie chastises him. Isaac tells Clara it is time for him to stop his search, but she makes him ignore the data and focus on his inner connection to the universe. He is surprised when it works, but rejects it and her. She grabs her bag to leave - and collapses.\n\nAt the hospital, it is revealed that Clara has an autoimmune disease that is causing the complete breakdown of every organ and muscle in her body. The doctors are shocked that she can even walk or talk, and confirm she will soon be dead. Isaac stays at her bedside for her last few days. Moments before she dies, she tells him he is going to \u201csee it\u201d.\n\nA fresh batch of TESS data is released, and Isaac does \u201csee it\u201d - proof of a seemingly artificial object in coincident orbit with an exoplanet. He takes his findings to Charlie, who introduces him to Dr. Rickman, head of the TESS project. Two years later, at a press conference at the [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory|JPL]], Dr. Rickman, Rebecca and Charlie explain that the data gathered now conclusively proves the existence of the artificial object, orbiting a star 200 light years distant, in turn proving the existence of intelligent alien life. Isaac is not in his assigned seat on the panel, choosing instead to spend time reminiscing about Clara.\n\nA few months later, Rebecca summons Isaac to the [[Search for extraterrestrial intelligence|SETI]] laboratory. She reveals that the aliens have sent a message&mdash;\u201cIsaac Bruno\u201d. He is present when the next message arrives &ndash; an audio file of a [[Bob Dylan]] song that he and Clara often listened to together. The film ends with Isaac smiling through his tears.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Patrick J. Adams]] as Dr. Isaac Bruno \n* [[Troian Bellisario]] as Clara\n* [[Ennis Esmer]] as Dr. Charlie Durant \n* [[Kristen Hager]] as Dr. Rebecca Jenkins \n* [[R. H. Thomson]] as Dr. Rickman\n* [[Jennifer Dale]] as Astrophysics Department Head\n\n==Themes and genre==\nA story about \"space and love\",<ref name=\"Slotek\">{{cite web |last1=Slotek |first1=Jim (interviewer) |title=Original-Cin Review/Q&A: Clara Filmmaker Shoots for the Stars (and Mostly Reaches \u2018Em, Too) |url=https://www.original-cin.ca/posts/2018/11/27/original-cin-reviewqampa-clara-filmmaker-shoots-for-the-stars-and-mostly-reaches-em-too |website=Original-Cin.ca |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Sherman titled the film ''Clara'' because the word means \"clear\" and \"bright,\" like a star: \"it was about this search for life among the stars.\"<ref name=\"Billings\">{{cite journal |last1=Billings |first1=Lee (interviewer) |title=''Clara'' Is a Story of Exoplanets, Existential Longing\u2014and Real Science |journal=[[Scientific American]] |date=11 October 2018 |url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/clara-is-a-story-of-exoplanets-existential-longing-mdash-and-real-science1/ |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Sherman did not consider the film [[romantic film|romantic]], but anticipated it would be marketed that way \"because the lead actors are married in real life\"; it is a love story to the extent that there is \"a binding bond between two characters\" who are \"just two people connecting for a bit.\"<ref name=\"Slotek\" />\n\n==Production==\n===Background and writing===\nSherman studied at [[Ryerson University|Ryerson]]'s film school for one year, where one day, at 19, he became determined to write a story, shutting himself in his dormitory room for seven hours.<ref name=\"Slotek\" /> \n\nFriends Sherman made at Ryerson worked with him on his debut, ''The Rocket List'', \"made on no budget ... on a four-day road trip with a camera,\"<ref name=\"Malyk\">{{cite journal |last1=Malyk |first1=Lauren |title=TIFF \u201918: The winning formula behind Akash Sherman\u2019s Clara |journal=[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]] |date=10 September 2018 |url=https://playbackonline.ca/2018/09/10/clara-a-sci-fi-stepping-stone/ |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> as well as on ''Clara''.<ref name=\"Slotek\" /> Together with James Ewasiuk, a \"close collaborator\" who co-wrote ''The Rocket List'' with him, Sherman did four months of research on \"the Kepler telescope and transits and things like that.\"<ref name=\"Slotek\" />\n\nBoth romantic leads contributed ideas. Adams was involved with the project from an early stage, giving feedback to Sherman on his script, on character in particular, which the director began revising in earnest at age 20 and finished two years later.<ref name=\"Knight\" /> Bellisario provided \"a similar depth for her character,\" and suggested a different ending for the film, a note which Sherman accepted: \"I had a different ending in mind, which I don't want to share because it's not as good.\"<ref name=\"Knight\" /> It was Bellisario who brought up [[quantum entanglement]] for one of the earlier drafts.<ref name=\"Slotek\" /> \n\n====Scientific accuracy====\nThe detection method and the specialized telescopes depicted in ''Clara'' are not fictional. The [[Transiting Exoplanet Survey Satellite|TESS]] space telescope is a 2018 upgrade of the [[Kepler Telescope]] which was used to discover over 4000 [[exoplanets]] iin the decade since 2009.<ref name=\"Shanahan\">{{cite web |last1=Shanahan |first1=Don |title=Clara Grounds Solemnity and Sweetness Into Complicated Love Within Science Fiction |url=https://25yearslatersite.com/2019/09/19/clara-grounds-solemnity-and-sweetness-into-complicated-love-within-science-fiction/ |website=25YearsLaterSite.com |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Sherman gave a talk on the science behind the film at the Astronomy On Tap event in Toronto on 17 August 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"The Science of CLARA\" - Akash Sherman at Astronomy On Tap, Toronto HD |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2nFL-thbPP0 |website=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Sherman relied on three scientific advisors, Canadian astrophysicists John Moores and Doug Welch,<ref name=\"Billings\" /> at [[York University|York]] and [[McMaster University|McMaster]] universities respectively, and Barth Netterfeld of the [[University of Toronto]]:  \"Almost everything was vetted by them. It,s so vetted, in fact, that the climactic discovery in the movie... turned out to be an original idea\", later published by the [[American Astronomical Society]].<ref name=\"Slotek\" />\n\n===Financing===\n''Clara'' was produced by Serendipity Point in association with [[London]]-based Distant Horizon, with the support of [[Telefilm Canada]], the Ontario Media Development Corporation, the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]], and [[Bell Media]]'s [[The Movie Network|TMN]].<ref name=\"Pinto\">{{cite journal |last1=Pinto |first1=Jordan |title=Production begins on Serendipity Point\u2019s Clara |journal=[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]] |date=7 March 2017 |url=http://playbackonline.ca/2017/03/07/production-begins-on-serendipity-points-clara/ |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] took place in [[Toronto]] during the month of March in 2017.<ref name=\"Pinto\" /> Leads Adams and Bellisario were married a little earlier,<ref name=\"Knight\">{{cite news |last1=Knight |first1=Chris |title=Akash Sherman looks to the cosmos for Clara, his second feature film |url=https://nationalpost.com/entertainment/movies/akash-sherman-looks-to-the-cosmos-for-clara-his-second-feature-film |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=[[The National Post]] |date=November 28, 2018}}</ref> and spent a large portion of their [[honeymoon]] working on the film.<ref name=\"Collider\">{{cite web |title=Clara: Patrick J. Adams, Ari Lantos, and Director Akash Sherman on Their Grounded Sci-Fi Film [Collider interview] |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TFHtf7vTBmg |website=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=17 April 2020 |format=video}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nComposer Jonathan Kawchuk wrote a \"soft score\", complimenting musical selections by [[Bob Dylan]].<ref name=\"Shanahan\" />\n\n==Release==\n''Clara'' premiered at the [[2018 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref>[https://nowtoronto.com/movies/tiff-2018-canadian-films-rob-stewart/ \"TIFF 2018: Rob Stewart, Denys Arcand, Jennifer Baichwal films among Canadian titles\"]. ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]'', 1 August 2018.</ref> This was followed by a [[limited theatrical release]].<ref name=\"Shanahan\" />\n\n===Distribution===\nD Films was responsible for ''Clara's'' Canadian theatrical distribution, while the CBC holds the television broadcast rights, and TMN holds the [[pay TV]] rights.<ref name=\"Pinto\" />\n\n===Home media and streaming===\n''Clara'' is available on DVD<ref>{{cite web |title=Clara (DVD) - Walmart.com |url=https://www.pinterest.com/pin/112027109497857701/ |website=[[Pinterest]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> and Blu-ray.<ref>{{cite web |title=Clara |url=https://www.blu-ray.com/Clara/1139480/ |website=Blu-ray.com |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe film is available on [[video on demand]] platforms<ref name=\"Shanahan\" /> such as [[Amazon Prime]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Clara |url=https://www.amazon.com/Clara-Patrick-J-Adams/dp/B07RJ1T87C |website=[[Amazon.com]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception== \n===Critical response===\n''Clara'' has a critic review score of 48% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 23 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |title=Clara (2018) |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/clara_2018/ |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which uses a weighted score, the film has a score of 43 out of 100 based on six reviews.<ref>{{cite web |title=Clara |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/clara |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAssigning the film 2 stars at [[RogerEbert.com]], Peter Sobczynski called the film \"peculiar and largely unsatisfying\" despite the ambitions displayed by Akash Sherman: \"the result is a weird muddle that's both too silly to be taken seriously and too staid to completely go off the beaten path.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sobczynski |first1=Peter |title=Clara |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/clara-2019 |website=RogerEbert.com |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Toronto critic Norman Wilner, writing for ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]'', though conceding the film has its moments, feels that the story stops where it ought to have begun.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilner |first1=Norman |title=Review: Toronto-set Clara stops just where it ought to begin |url=https://nowtoronto.com/movies/reviews/review-clara-akash-sherman/ |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=[[Now (newspaper)|Now]] |date=November 28, 2018}}</ref> Tara Thorne finds that ''Clara'' has \"outsized ideas that dominate and weaken the film beneath it\", lacking in humour but featuring too much \"data talk\", though it finally gains traction in the last twenty minutes, a \"big reveal\" that pays off but also sacrifices genuine emotions for \"dutifully plotted emotional beats.\" Having said all this, Thorne calls Sherman an \"assured director who clearly has big plans.\"<ref name=\"Thorne\">{{cite news |last1=Thorne |first1=Tara |title=Film review: Clara |url=https://www.thecoast.ca/halifax/film-review-clara/Content?oid=19372258 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=The Coast |date=November 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nUnlike Thorne, Don Shanahan finds the real life science as an \"interwoven backdrop\" provides a \"narrative boon for the science fiction of ''Clara''.\" Its \"sense of intelligence intertwines with the unpredictability found in the amorous reverberations of the human heart\", a combination which makes for an \"intimate and daring film experience\", a \"rare treat\" to have \"two narrative genres combined with smarts and affection.\"<ref name=\"Shanahan\" /> Writing for ''[[Exclaim!]]'', Alex Hudson finds the science more intriguing than what he calls the film's philosophical musings, but, despite its flaws, it works as a mood piece: \"the colours are muted, the score is appropriately etherial, and it effectively captures Isaac's depression as he searches for meaning in his broken life. It gets under the skin even when it doesn't stimulate the mind.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hudson |first1=Alex |title='Clara' Is an Ambitious Hunt for the Meaning of Life |journal=[[Exclaim!]] |date=December 3, 2018 |url=http://exclaim.ca/film/article/tiff_review_clara_is_an_ambitious_hunt_for_the_meaning_of_life-directed_by_akash_sherman |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nGiving the film a B rating, Jim Slotek calls ''Clara a \"solidly written\" that \"shows a sure-handed storytelling career that's just getting started\", benefiting from NASA\u2013provided photos and effects \"cannily\" used to give it \"the look of a much higher budgeted movie\".<ref name=\"Slotek\" />\n\n===Scientific response and influence===\nThe film's trailer, due both to \"lush\" visual effects and \"teasing science-savvy plot points\" attracted a lot of attention on social media from astronomers,<ref name=\"Billings\" /> and led to a mention in a science journal for Sherman's \"innovative thoughts on how to search for life in other star systems.\"<ref name=\"Slotek\" />\n\nIsaac and Clara's use of publicly available data from [[NASA]]'s TESS has \"surprisingly robust real-world roots\" in a \"''Clara''-inspired academic paper\" written by the scientific advisors, published in ''[[Research Notes of the American Astronomical Society]]''.<ref name=\"Billings\" /> The article, titled \"Simulating Transits at the L1 Point\", shares credit with Sherman. \"They credited me as a scientist. I'm published! So, that's really cool.\"<ref name=\"Slotek\" />\n\n===Accolades===\n====Award====\n*[[Austin Film Festival]], 2018 \u2022 Jury Award for a Narrative Feature (Akash Sherman and James Ewasiuk)<ref>{{cite web |title=2018 Winners |url=https://austinfilmfestival.com/blog/festival-and-conference/2018-winners/ |website=[[Austin Film Festival]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Nominations====\n;2018\n*[[Directors Guild of Canada]] Discovery Award;<ref>{{cite web |title=Discovery Award Long List 2018 |url=https://www.dgc.ca/en/national/news/discovery-award-long-list-2018/ |website=dcg.ca |publisher=[[Directors Guild of Canada]] |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> [[shortlist]]ed (1 of 4)<ref>{{cite web |title=Directors Guild presents: Visionaries at TIFF |url=https://www.dgc.ca/visionaries/visionaries/ |website=dcg.ca |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> \n*[[Vancouver Film Critics Circle]] One to Watch Award and Best Best Actress in a Canadian Film<ref>{{cite web |title=Vancouver Film Critics Circle Award Nominations |url=https://theawardspsychic.blogspot.com/2018/12/vancouver-film-critics-circle-award.html |website=The Awards Psychic |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n;2019\n*[[Golden Trailer Awards]] Best Foreign Poster<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hipes |first1=Patrick |title=Golden Trailer Awards Nominations: \u2018A Star Is Born\u2019, Netflix Lead Way |journal=Deadline |date=9 May 2019 |url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/golden-trailer-awards-nominees-2019-nominations-list-netflix-a-star-is-born-1202610742/ |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.facebook.com/CLARATheFilm/ Official page] on [[Facebook]]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7eIbm4cfA8M Official trailer] on [[YouTube]]\n* {{IMDb title|6613878}}\n\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:2010s science fiction films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Canadian science fiction films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n", "name_user": "ZarhanFastfire", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCritical response", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clara_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Crispin Freeman", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Crispin Freeman\n| image = Crispin Freeman.jpg\n| caption = Crispin in 2009, after teaching at the JVTA-LA.\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1972|2|9}}\n| birth_place = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], U.S.<ref>{{cite tweet | user=CrispinFreeman | last=Freeman | first=Crispin | number=454420609045647361 | date=April 11, 2014 | title=A primeval forest sounds lovely! I was born in Chicago and never found one there. Show us where it is! | accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref>\n| residence = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crispinfreeman.com/about/|title=About - Crispin Freeman|publisher=Crispin Freeman Productions|accessdate=August 22, 2016}}</ref>\n| education = [[Williams College]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[Columbia University]] {{small|([[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]])}}\n| occupation = Voice actor, ADR director, script writer\n| agent = Arlene Thornton and Associates\n| spouse = <!-- NEED SOURCE {{marriage|Izobel Carol|2007}} -->\n| relatives = [[Cassidy Freeman]] (sister)\n| website = {{url|http://www.crispinfreeman.com/}}\n<!-- NEED SOURCE |  birthname = Crispin McDougal Freeman -->\n| yearsactive = 1997\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Crispin Freeman''' (born February 9, 1972)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/search/record/results?count=20&query=+givenname:Crispin~++surname:Freeman~++birth_year:1972-1972~++record_country:%22United+States%22|title=FamilySearch|website=familysearch.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet | user=CrispinFreeman | last=Freeman | first=Crispin | number=8865075029 | date=February 9, 2010 | title=Thanks to everyone for all the birthday well wishes! I'm overwhelmed! | accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref> is an American voice actor, [[automated dialogue replacement|ADR]] director and writer who provides voices for English versions of Japanese anime, animation and video games.  In anime, some of his prominent roles include [[List of Slayers characters#Zelgadis Graywords|Zelgadis Graywords]] in ''[[Slayers]]'', [[List of Haruhi Suzumiya characters#Kyon|Kyon]] in ''[[The Melancholy of Haruhi Suzumiya]]'', [[Alucard (Hellsing)|Alucard]] in ''[[Hellsing]]'', [[List of Fate/Zero characters|Kirei Kotomine]] in ''[[Fate/Zero]]'' and ''[[Fate/stay night: Unlimited Blade Works]]'', [[Itachi Uchiha]] in ''[[Naruto]]'', and [[List of Durarara!! characters|Shizuo Heiwajima]] in ''[[Durarara!!]]''.\n\n==Early life and education==\n{{No footnotes|section|BLP=yes|date=May 2016}}\nBorn in [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], [[Illinois]], Freeman is the oldest of three children. He attended the [[Latin School of Chicago]], where he graduated in 1990. He earned his [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree from [[Williams College]], majoring in [[Theater]] and minoring in [[Computer Science]]. Afterward, he earned his [[Master of Fine Arts]] degree from [[Columbia University]] in [[Acting]] and performed on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] (New York City), at the [[American Repertory Theater]] in (Cambridge), at the [[Mark Taper Forum]] in (Los Angeles), at Cincinnati's Playhouse in the Park and at the Williamstown Theater Festival. As a child, Freeman was greatly influenced by [[anime]] shows such as ''[[Speed Racer]]'' and ''[[Battle of the Planets]]''. [[Casey Kasem]] voiced the role of his favorite character, Mark of ''Battle of the Planets'' (he actually wanted to change his name to Mark at one point). Later, he discovered ''[[Voltron]]'', ''[[Star Blazers]]'' and ''[[Robotech]]'', being quoted in the January 1999 issue of ''America Interview'' saying, \"That show really blew me away.\" Freeman has also stated that the reason he got into the industry was because of the anime television show ''[[The Vision of Escaflowne]]''. Freeman initially got involved in the anime voice-over industry when a friend of his landed a role in ''[[Peacock King]]''.\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Crispin Freeman at Super-Con 2009 5.JPG|thumb|right|Crispin Freeman at Super-Con 2009]]\n{{More footnotes|section|BLP=yes|date=May 2016}}\nKnowing Freeman was a big anime fan, a friend suggested he call up [[Central Park Media]] (CPM) and apply for a job doing English dubs. When originally approached about dubbing, he initially declined. It was not until he remembered all of the anime shows he watched as a child that he realized that many people are introduced to anime through the English dubbed versions. In 1997, Freeman landed the role of [[List of Slayers characters#Zelgadis Graywords|Zelgadis Graywords]] in ''[[Slayers]]'' along with [[Lisa Ortiz]], [[Eric Stuart]] and [[Veronica Taylor]]. He was the second and final voice actor to get the job, after Zelgadis' original voice actor, Daniel Cronin, lost contact with CPM after a year-long halt in the dubbing. Years later he turned to the American animation voice acting grounds. He has been best known for his work in [[Marvel Comics]] based productions such as ''[[The Spectacular Spider-Man (TV series)|The Spectacular Spider-Man]]'', ''[[Wolverine and the X-Men (TV series)|Wolverine and the X-Men]]'' and ''[[The Avengers: Earth's Mightiest Heroes]]''. He then starred as several versions of [[Roy Harper (comics)|Roy Harper]] in ''[[Young Justice (TV series)|Young Justice]]'' for [[DC Comics]] and [[Warner Bros.]] Since then, Freeman has had various roles throughout his career. He has appeared in many video game titles as memorable characters, such as [[Albedo]] from [[Namco]]'s [[Xenosaga]] series, the god of the sun ''[[Helios]]'' in ''[[God of War III]]'', Haji, Joel the 6th and Van Argeno in ''[[Blood+]]'', the main protagonist [[Baldur]] in Silicon Knights's ''[[Too Human]]'', [[Breakdown (Transformers)|Breakdown]] in ''[[Transformers: War for Cybertron]]'', the [[Winter Soldier (comics)|Winter Soldier]] in ''[[Marvel: Ultimate Alliance]]'', and [[Iron Man]] in ''[[Marvel: Ultimate Alliance 2]]''.\n\nFreeman teaches classes, workshops, and performance lectures in the Los Angeles area.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://crispinfreeman.com/classes.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-11-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111103050156/http://www.crispinfreeman.com/classes.html |archive-date=2011-11-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  In addition to classes, Freeman has a website called Voice Acting Mastery which includes podcasts and other resources regarding voice acting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voiceactingmastery.com|title=Voice Acting Mastery: Become a Master Voice Actor in the World of Voice Over - Become the Character. Live the Dream. Find Yourself.|website=Voice Acting Mastery: Become a Master Voice Actor in the World of Voice Over}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n<!-- NEED SOURCE On August 11, 2007, he married Izobel Carol on the island of [[Hawaii]] at the Mauna Kea Beach Hotel. In October 2009, Crispin hosted two virtual town halls on Vokle.com. He took questions from fans, did character voices and read his favorite scary story.{{citation needed|date=January 2015|reason=need news source for this}}\n-->Freeman is the oldest of three children. His sister, [[Cassidy Freeman|Cassidy]] is an actress who played [[Tess Mercer]] in the television show ''[[Smallville (TV series)|Smallville]]'' and Cady Longmire in ''[[Longmire (TV series)|Longmire]]''. Their brother, Clark, is an actor and musician; they are involved in a band called The Real D'Coys.<ref>[http://www.newsarama.com/tv/090501-cassidy-freeman.html 'Lex Schmex' \u2013 Meet SMALLVILLE's Tess Mercer] Newsarama.com</ref> Their family has German, Scottish, and Jewish ancestry.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n==Filmography==\n===Anime===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ List of dubbing performances in anime\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Source<ref name=\"resume\"/>\n|-\n| {{dts|1998}} || ''[[Revolutionary Girl Utena]]'' || Toga Kiryu, Dios ||  || <!-- crystal acids -->\n|-\n| {{dts|1998}}&ndash;200