=SAS Group Year\u2010end report November2012 \u2013 October2013|publisher=SAS Group |accessdate=14 March 2014}}</ref>\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sasgroup.net/en/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2015/01/SAS-Annual-Report-20132014.pdf |title=SAS Group Annual Report with Sustainability Review November 2013\u2013October 2014|publisher=SAS Group |accessdate=1 March 2015}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|<ref name=\"SAS Annual Report 2018\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sasgroup.net/en/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2019/01/sas-sas-annual-report-fiscal-year-2018-190129.pdf |title=SAS Annual Report Fiscal Year 2018|publisher=SAS Group |accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref>\n|<ref name=\"SAS Annual Report 2018\"/>\n|}\n</center>\n\n===Head office===\n[[File:SAS koncernbyggnad 2007.jpg|thumb|The current head office, the [[SAS Fr\u00f6sundavik Office Building]] as seen in 2007.]]\nScandinavian Airlines' head office is located in the [[SAS Fr\u00f6sundavik Office Building]] in {{Interlanguage link multi|Fr\u00f6sundavik|sv}}, [[Solna Municipality]], Sweden, near [[Stockholm]].<ref name=fastighetsvarlden/> Between 2011 and 2013, the head office was located at [[Stockholm-Arlanda Airport|Stockholm Arlanda Airport (ARN)]] in [[Sigtuna Municipality]], Sweden.<ref>[http://www.flysas.com/en/Generic/Help_Contact/Contact_us/SAS_Head_offices/SAS_head_office_-_Sweden/?PreviewURL=True \"SAS Head Office in Sweden.\"] Scandinavian Airlines. Retrieved on 27 January 2012. \"SAS Head Office Stockholm-Arlanda Kabinv\u00e4gen 5 SE-195 87 Stockholm\"</ref> The SAS Cargo Group A/S head office is in [[Kastrup]], [[T\u00e5rnby Municipality]], Denmark.<ref>\"[http://www.sascargo.com/Contact/Headquarters.aspx Headquarters].\" SAS Cargo. Retrieved on 27 January 2012. \"Visiting address Kystvejen 40 DK-2770 Kastrup Denmark\"</ref>\n\nThe SAS Fr\u00f6sundavik Office Building,<ref>\"[http://www.flysas.com/en/Generic/Help_Contact/Contact_us/SAS_Head_offices/SAS_head_office_-_Sweden/ SAS head office in Sweden].\" Scandinavian Airlines. Retrieved on 8 June 2009.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.solna.se/Global/Stadsbyggnad%20och%20trafik/Kartor/Cykelkarta2007.pdf Cykelkarta 2007].\" [[Solna Municipality]]. Retrieved on 12 February 2010.</ref> was designed by [[Niels Torp|Niels Torp Architects]] and built between 1985 and 1987. The move from Solna to Arlanda was completed in 2010.<ref>\"[http://feed.ne.cision.com/wpyfs/00/00/00/00/00/15/EB/65/wkr0005.pdf Interim Report January-June 2011].\" Retrieved 30 December 2012.</ref> A previous SAS head office was located on the grounds of [[Bromma Airport]] in [[Stockholm Municipality|Stockholm]].<ref>\"World Airline Directory.\" ''[[Flight International]]''. 29 March 1986. [http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1986/1986%20-%200782.html?search=\"Scandinavian Airlines System\" 122].</ref><!--This is not in the current Scandinavian Airlines head office article--> In 2013 SAS announced that it once again would relocate to Fr\u00f6sundavik.<ref name=fastighetsvarlden>{{Cite web|title=SAS flyttar \u00e5ter till Fr\u00f6sunda \u2013 n\u00e4ra 14000 kvm aktuellt|publisher=Tidnings AB Fastighetsv\u00e4rlden|url=http://www.fastighetsvarlden.se/notiser/sas-flyttar-ater-till-frosunda-nara-14000-kvm-aktuellt/|accessdate=2015-07-22 |url-status=live|archiveurl=|archivedate=}}</ref>\n\n==Emissions==\nAs for other airlines, burned fossil fuel and emitted greenhouse gases are significant side effects from the company activities. The following table gives and overview of emissions of greenhouse gases in [[Carbon dioxide equivalent|CO<sub>2</sub>e]] emitted by the company as reported in the [[European Union Emission Trading Scheme]]. Data for passengers, aircraft and profit from section Business Trends above.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\" style=\"text-align:right;\n|+Verified emissions as reported in [[EU ETS]]\n!style=\"text-align:left; | '''Year'''\n!2013\n!2014\n!2015\n!2016\n!2017\n!2018\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left; | Emissions ([[tonnes]] CO<sub>2</sub>e)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/clima/sites/clima/files/ets/registry/docs/verified_emissions_2018_en.xlsx|title=Verified emissions 2018|publisher=European Union emissions trading system (EU ETS)|accessdate=2019-11-28}}</ref>\n|{{val|2334686}}\n|{{val|2366299}}\n|{{val|2357470}}\n|{{val|2432546}}\n|{{val|2485804}}\n|{{val|2466820}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left; | Passengers (millions)\n|30.4\n|29.4\n|28.1\n|29.4\n|30.1\n|30.1\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left; | Emissions per passenger (kg)\n|77\n|80\n|84\n|83\n|83\n|82\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left; | Aircraft\n|139\n|138\n|152\n|156\n|158\n|157\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left; | Emissions per aircraft (tonnes CO<sub>2</sub>e)\n|{{val|16796}}\n|{{val|17147}}\n|{{val|15510}}\n|{{val|15593}}\n|{{val|15733}}\n|{{val|15712}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left; | Profit (million SEK)\n|{{val|1648}}\n|{{val|-918}}\n|{{val|1417}}\n|{{val|1431}}\n|{{val|1725}}\n|{{val|2041}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left; | Profit per emissions (SEK/tonne)\n|{{val|706}}\n|{{val|-388}}\n|{{val|601}}\n|{{val|588}}\n|{{val|694}}\n|{{val|827}}\n|}\n\nIn contrast to most other businesses and private individuals in Sweden, airlines are exempt from the Swedish carbon tax. Had SAS paid the Swedish carbon tax level of SEK{{nbsp}}1180 (EUR{{nbsp}}114) per tonne ({{as of|2019|lc=y}})<ref>{{cite web |title=Sweden\u2019s carbon tax |url=https://www.government.se/government-policy/taxes-and-tariffs/swedens-carbon-tax/ |publisher=Swedish Government |accessdate=12 December 2019 |date=January 2019}}</ref> for all of its emissions, it would have had significant impact on recent profit levels. Since 2012 [[European Union Emission Trading Scheme#Aviation emissions|airlines are included]] in the [[EU ETS]]. In January 2013 the price for extra emission rights on top of the granted were approximately [[European Union Emission Trading Scheme#Phase III|EUR 6.3 per tonne]]. In May 2017 the price was EUR 4.9 per tonne.<ref>{{cite web |title=Forecast for EU carbon prices in next decade put Paris target in doubt |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-europe-carbontrading-idUSKBN18K0ZK |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=12 December 2019 |date=May 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Destinations==\n{{main|List of Scandinavian Airlines destinations}}\n{{further|List of SAS Group destinations}}\n\n===Codeshare agreements===\nScandinavian Airlines has [[codeshare agreement]]s with the following airlines:<ref name=\"CAPA SAS profile\">{{cite web|url=http://centreforaviation.com/profiles/airlines/sas-sk |title=Profile on SAS |website=CAPA|publisher=Centre for Aviation|access-date=2016-10-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030174236/http://centreforaviation.com/profiles/airlines/sas-sk |archive-date=2016-10-30|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=17em}}\n* [[Aegean Airlines]]\n* [[Air Canada]]\n* [[Air China]]\n* [[airBaltic]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Liu |first1=Jim |title=airBaltic resumes SAS codeshare partnership from June 2019 |url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/284491/airbaltic-resumes-sas-codeshare-partnership-from-june-2019/ |accessdate=24 May 2019 |work=Routesonline |date=24 May 2019}}</ref>\n* [[All Nippon Airways]]\n* [[Austrian Airlines]]\n* [[Croatia Airlines]]\n* [[EgyptAir]]\n* [[Ethiopian Airlines]]\n* [[Etihad Airways]]\n* [[Icelandair]]\n* [[LOT Polish Airlines]]\n* [[Lufthansa]]\n* [[Luxair]] <ref>{{cite news |last1=Liu |first1=Jim |title=Luxair / SAS begins codeshare service from March 2017 |url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/272033/luxair-sas-begins-codeshare-service-from-march-2017/ |accessdate=6 January 2020 |work=Routesonline |date=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Singapore Airlines]]\n* [[South African Airways]]\n* [[Swiss International Air Lines]]\n* [[Thai Airways]]\n* [[Turkish Airlines]]\n* [[United Airlines]]\n* [[Wider\u00f8e]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Interline agreements===\nScandinavian Airlines has [[interlining|interlining agreements]] with the following airlines:\n{|\n|- valign=\"top\"\n* [[Air Greenland]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airgreenland.com/about/news/air-greenland-og-sas-indgaar-ny-og-udvidet-samarbejdsaftale |title=AIR GREENLAND AND SAS ENTERS A NEW AND ENHANCED COOPERATION|publisher=Airgreenland.com |date=2013-08-21 |accessdate=2014-03-17}}</ref>\n* [[Pakistan International Airlines]]<ref name=\"PIA Codeshare and Interline\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.piac.com.pk/interline-travel|title=INTERLINE AND CODESHARE TRAVEL|website=Pakistan International Airlines}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Fleet==\n{{main|List of Scandinavian Airlines aircraft}}\n\n===Current fleet===\n{{As of|2020|3}}, Scandinavian Airlines operates the following aircraft:<ref>{{cite web|author= 31 July 2013|url=http://www.sasgroup.net/SASGroup/default.asp |title=The SAS Group's fleet in traffic |publisher=sasgroup.net|accessdate=2014-05-09}}{{dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=13 February 2014|url=http://www.planespotters.net/Airline/SAS|title=SAS Fleet in Planespotters.net|publisher=planespotters.net |accessdate=2019-10-07}}{{dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse; text-align:center; margin: 1em auto;\"\n|+ Scandinavian Airlines fleet\n|- \n! rowspan=\"2\" | Aircraft\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:60px;\" |In service\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:25px;\" | Orders\n! colspan=\"4\" | Passengers\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Notes\n|- \n! <abbr title=\"SAS Business\">C</abbr>\n! <abbr title=\"SAS Plus\">Y</abbr>\n! <abbr title=\"SAS Go\">M</abbr>\n! Total\n|-\n|[[Airbus A319-100]]\n|4\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|150\n|150\n|\n|-\n|[[Airbus A320-200]]\n|11\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|168\n|168\n|\n|-\n|[[Airbus A320neo]]\n|30\n|41<ref name=\"sas a320neo\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sasgroup.net/en/sas-places-order-for-an-additional-50-airbus-a320neo-aircraft-to-create-a-single-type-fleet/|title=SAS places order for an additional 50 Airbus A320neo aircraft to create a single-type fleet - SAS|website=SAS|accessdate=3 October 2018}}</ref>\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|180\n|180\n|Deliveries until 2023.\n|-\n|[[Airbus A321-200]]\n|8\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|200\n|200\n|\n|-\n|[[Airbus A321LR]]\n|&mdash;\n|3<ref name=\"sas a321lr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sasgroup.net/en/sas-expands-its-fleet-leases-three-a321-long-range/|title=SAS expands its fleet \u2013 leases three A321 Long Range - SAS|website=SAS|accessdate=23 January 2019}}</ref>\n|22\n|12\n|123\n|157\n|Deliveries from 2020.<ref>https://www.di.se/live/nu-ar-det-klart-nar-sas-nya-mindre-plan-lyfter/</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Airbus A330-300]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|9\n|rowspan=\"2\"|&mdash;\n|32\n|56\n|174\n|262\n|rowspan=\"2\"|\n|-\n|32\n|56\n|178\n|266\n|-\n|[[Airbus A340-300]]\n|4\n|&mdash;\n|40\n|28\n|179\n|247\n|One painted in [[Star Alliance]] livery.<br>To be replaced by Airbus A350-900.<ref name=\"twitter\">{{cite web |last1=SAS - Scandinavian Airlines (@SAS) |title=Hello again! The A350\u2019s will replace the A340\u2019s. We plan to retire the them in the south of France where they will be dimantled and the useful parts sold. Kind regards, Alice |url=https://twitter.com/SAS/status/1182985156270923777 |website=Twitter |accessdate=30 January 2020 |date=12 October 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Airbus A350-900]]\n|3\n|5<ref name=\"Airbus\">{{cite press release|date= 25 June 2013|url=http://www.airbus.com/newsevents/news-events-single/detail/sas-selects-eight-a350-xwbs-and-four-a330s |title=SAS selects eight A350 XWBs and four A330s |publisher=Airbus |accessdate=2013-06-25}}</ref>\n|40\n|32\n|228\n|300\n|Deliveries until 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.cision.com/sas/r/sas-signs-with-airbus--total-renewal-of-long-haul-fleet,c9433383 |title=SAS signs with Airbus: Total renewal of long haul fleet - SAS |publisher=News.cision.com |date=2013-06-25 |accessdate=2014-03-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Aircraft on order |url=https://www.sasgroup.net/en/aircraft-on-order/ |website=SAS |accessdate=8 October 2019}}</ref><br>Replacing Airbus A340-300.<ref name=\"twitter\"/>\n|-\n|[[Boeing 737-700]]\n|22\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|141\n|141\n|To be replaced by Airbus A320neo.<ref name=airbusflaade>{{cite web|url=http://www.check-in.dk/sas-styrer-mod-ren-airbus-flaade/|title=SAS styrer mod ren Airbus-fl\u00e5de - CHECK-IN.dk}}</ref>\n|-\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Boeing 737-800]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|27\n|rowspan=\"2\"|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|181\n|181\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Three painted in [[Star Alliance]] livery.<br>To be replaced by Airbus A320neo.<ref name=\"sas a320neo\" />\n|-\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|183\n|183\n|-\n|-\n! colspan=\"8\" |Wet-leased aircraft\n|-\n|[[Airbus A320neo]]\n|9\n|\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|180\n|180\n|Operated by [[Scandinavian Airlines Ireland]]\n|-\n|[[ATR 72|ATR 72-600]]\n|8\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|&mdash;\n|70\n|70\n|Operated by [[Nordica (airline)|Xfly]] \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Bombardier CRJ900]]\n|19\n| rowspan=\"2\" |&mdash;\n| rowspan=\"2\" |&mdash;\n| rowspan=\"2\" |&mdash;\n| rowspan=\"2\" |90\n| rowspan=\"2\" |90\n|Operated by [[CityJet]]\n|-\n|3\n|Operated by [[Nordica (airline)|Xfly]] \n|-\n|-\n!Total\n!157\n!49\n! colspan=\"5\" |\n|}\n</center>\n\n===Future fleet plans===\n====Short haul====\n[[File:LN-RGO A320neo (31659446490).jpg|thumb|right|A SAS [[Airbus A320neo]] in 2017.]]\nOn 20 June 2011, SAS announced an order for 30 new [[A320neo]] aircraft as part of its fleet harmonisation plan.<ref name=\"airwaysmag\">{{cite web |title=Scandinavian Airlines Takes Delivery of First Airbus A320neo |url=https://airwaysmag.com/airlines/scandinavian-airlines-takes-delivery-first-airbus-a320neo/ |magazine=Airways Magazine|accessdate=22 June 2018}}</ref> SAS' stated goal is to have an all-Airbus fleet at its bases in Stockholm and Copenhagen by 2019, with a mixed A320neo and A320ceo fleet operation at both bases. The base in Oslo will then operate mostly Boeing 737-800 aircraft, with a few 737-700s also being retained. The older, smaller 737-600s are disposed in 2019.<ref name=airbusflaade /> The first of the order of A320neos was delivered in October 2016.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Caswell |first1=Mark |title=SAS takes delivery of first A320 neo \u2013 Business Traveller |url=https://www.businesstraveller.com/business-travel/2016/10/27/sas-takes-delivery-first-a320-neo/ |website=Business Traveller |accessdate=22 June 2018}}</ref>  In April 2018, SAS announced an order of 50 more A320neos to replace all 737NGs and older A320ceos in service as part of its goal to have an all-Airbus fleet by 2023.<ref name=\"sas a320neo\" />\n====Long haul====\nOn 25 June 2013, SAS and Airbus signed a Memorandum of Understanding stating that SAS intends to buy twelve new-generation aircraft, including six options. The agreement consists of eight A350-900s with six options and four A330-300Es. The first new long haul aircraft to enter service will be the A330-300E, which were originally planned to replace the aging A340-300s in 2015 as leasing agreements on these aircraft expire. Instead, SAS renewed the leasing agreements to be able to expand its long-haul fleet and used the new A330-300Es to add more long-haul destinations to its network. The A350-900 is planned to enter service in November 2019. SAS has dubbed this \"a total renewal of long haul fleet\", indicating that all former A340 and A330 will be replaced, although the total renewal could also refer to the new interior in the long haul fleet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://se.yhp.waymaker.net/sasgroup/release.asp?id=269175 |title=SAS Group - Press |publisher=Se.yhp.waymaker.net |date=2013-06-25 |accessdate=2014-03-17}}</ref>\n\nThe first of 8 Airbus A350-900s for SAS is expected to be delivered to the airline before the end of 2019 and to start to operate long haul routes from 28 January 2020.<ref>{{cite journal |title=SAS Scandinavian Airlines |journal=Airliner World |volume=August 2019 |page=11}}</ref> The A350 will first fly on the [[Copenhagen Airport|Copenhagen]] and [[O'Hare International Airport|Chicago]] route, with the airline planning [[Beijing Capital International Airport|Beijing]], [[Newark Liberty International Airport|New York]], [[Haneda Airport|Tokyo]], [[Shanghai Pudong International Airport|Shanghai]], [[Hong Kong International Airport|Hong Kong]] and [[San Francisco International Airport|San Francisco]] when more A350 are delivered in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sasgroup.net/en/sas-announces-first-a350-flights-and-features/|accessdate=25 October 2019|title=SAS announces first A350 flights and features}}</ref>\n\n===Removal of SAS Q400 fleet===\n{{Main|Dash 8 landing gear incidents}}\n[[File:Sas oy-kfe cr9.jpg|thumb|A [[Bombardier CRJ700#CRJ900|Bombardier CRJ900 NextGen]] at Copenhagen in 2011.]]\nIn September 2007, two separate incidents of similar landing gear failures occurred within four days of each other on SAS  Bombardier Q400 aircraft. A third incident occurred in October 2007. On 28 October 2007, in a move that was described as unique by the Swedish press, the board of directors announced that all 27 [[Bombardier Q400]] aircraft were to be removed from service due to the three landing gear failures.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://se.yhp.waymaker.net/sasgroup/release.asp?id=155746|title=SAS removes Dash 8 Q400 from service permanently|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102112035/http://se.yhp.waymaker.net/sasgroup/release.asp?id=155746|archivedate=2 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nA press release from SAS said that the company had reached a settlement with Bombardier and Goodrich, whereby the airline would receive [[Swedish krona|SEK]] one billion as compensation, while SAS would purchase 27 new aircraft, with an option of 24 more. These aircraft would consist of 13 of the [[Bombardier CRJ900]] Nextgen (10 to SAS and 3 to [[Estonian Air]]) and 14 of the updated Q400 Nextgen units (8 to [[airBaltic]] and 6 to [[Wider\u00f8e]]), with 7 additional options.<ref name=\"News. Airliner World : 7\">\"News.\" Airliner World : 7.</ref><ref>[http://e24.no/naeringsliv/article2303807.ece SAS f\u00e5r en milliard i krasj-erstatning] (\"SAS gets a billion in crash compensation\") e24.no 10 March 2008 {{in lang|no}}</ref> SAS received the first CRJ-900 on 3 December 2008.\n\nIn November 2007, it was revealed that the [[Swedish Civil Aviation Administration]] began an investigation and accused Scandinavian Airlines System of cutting corners during maintenance. The airline reportedly made 2,300 flights in which safety equipment was not up to standard.<ref name=\"cph1\">[http://www.cphpost.dk/get/103436.html \"Plane crash disaster narrowly avoided.\"] ''[[The Copenhagen Post]]'', 10 September 2007. Retrieved: 6 December 2009.</ref>\n\n===Livery===\n[[File:Scandinavian Airlines Airbus A319; OY-KBO@GVA;13.05.2010 572ah (4617825565).jpg|thumb|OY-KBO, named Christian Valdemar Viking at [[Geneva Airport]].]]\nThe current livery was introduced in 1998 and is designed by SthlmLab (Stockholm Design Lab). SAS aircraft look predominantly white, however, the fuselage is in a very light beige (Pantone Warm Gray 2/Pantone 9083C) with \"Scandinavian\" above the windows in silver lettering (Pantone 877) and \"Airlines\" below the windows in white. The typeface used is [[Rotis#Rotis Semi Serif|Rotis Semi Serif]]. The vertical stabiliser (and winglets) are painted blue (Pantone 2738C) with the classic white SAS logo on it. It is a variant of the traditional SAS logotype, slimmed slightly and stylised by the design company Stockholm Design Lab, as part of the SAS livery change. The engine casing is painted in scarlet (Pantone Warm Red/Pantone 179C) with the word Scandinavian in white, the [[thrust reversers]] in the colour of the fuselage. All other text is painted in Pantone Warm Gray 9. The design also features stylised versions of the Scandinavian flags. All aircraft are named, traditionally after Vikings.\n\nIn September 2019, SAS unveiled an all-new livery,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Scandinavian Way|url=https://www.flysas.com/en/newfleet/|website=www.flysas.com|publisher=Scandinavian Airlines System |accessdate=20 September 2019}}</ref> which will initially be showcased on a new A350 and an A320neo, before gradually being rolled out to the whole fleet.\n\nApart from the standard livery, SAS also has an Airbus A319 in [[retrojet|retro livery]] and two Boeing 737s and one Airbus A340 in Star Alliance livery.\n\n==Cabin==\n[[File:SAS Carvelle SE-210 (19).jpg|thumb|A Scandinavian Airlines flight attendant serving passengers in the 1960s.]]\n\n===SAS Business===\nOn long-haul flights business class, called ''SAS Business'', is still offered and features wide sleeper seats. On the [[Airbus A330]]s and upgraded [[Airbus A340]]s seating is 1-2-1 on seats that convert into {{convert|196|\u2013|202|cm}} flat beds, with power sockets and a {{convert|15|in}} entertainment screen.\n\n===SAS Plus===\nPlus is SAS' premium economy class. On wide-body aircraft, seating has a 2-3-2 configuration. The seats offered on SAS Plus are wider than those in the SAS Go section.\n\nOn European flights, SAS Plus tickets are refundable and include a meal, a double checked-in baggage allowance, and access to lounges and fast track security at the airport. The SAS Plus passengers are seated at the front of the aircraft and passengers can choose their seat at booking for free, but the seats there are otherwise the same as the SAS Go seats. The two-class system was introduced in June 2013, when [[business class]] was eliminated from intra-European flights.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.traveldailymedia.com/192395/sas-revamps-cabin-classes/|title=SAS revamps cabin classes|last=Elliott|first=Mark|publisher=Travel Daily Media|accessdate=12 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===SAS Go===\nSAS Go, or economy offers 3-3 seating on intracontinental flights, and 2-4-2 on the A330s and A340s.\n\nSAS offers free coffee and tea to GO passengers on short-haul services, except very short flights like [[Bergen Airport, Flesland|Bergen]]-[[Stavanger Airport, Sola|Stavanger]] or [[Stockholm Arlanda Airport|Stockholm]]-[[Visby Airport|Visby]]. Meals are served to all passengers on long-haul flights.\n\n===SAS Go Light===\nSAS Go Light is a variant of SAS Go with no checked luggage included. Tickets are sold in the same booking class as SAS Go and are otherwise identical. As of December 14, 2017, SAS Go Light is available on both European and Long-haul flights. It is not available on flights within the Nordic countries. SAS Go Light is aimed at competing with [[low-cost carriers]] for those who travel with hand luggage only. Extra luggage allowance for [[EuroBonus]] Silver, Gold, and Diamond members does not apply on SAS Go Light tickets and is only valid for EuroBonus Pandion members.\n\n==Services==\n===Fingerprint biometric identification===\nIn 2006, SAS Sweden launched a new [[biometric]] system for use throughout Sweden. Each passenger's fingerprints are, for security purposes, matched to their respective checked baggage. The new technology will be phased in at all the airports served by SAS, although the use of the system is voluntary for passengers. The system has been introduced in Norway.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sasgroup.net/en/fingerprint-recognition-to-be-introduced-at-arlanda-and-landvetter/ |title=Fingerprint recognition to be introduced at Arlanda and Landvetter |publisher = SAS |year = 2006}}</ref>\n\n===EuroBonus===\n{{Main|EuroBonus}}\nSAS's frequent-flyer program is called EuroBonus. Members earn points on all SAS and Wider\u00f8e flights as well as on Star Alliance flights. Around 50 percent of SAS\u2019 total revenues are generated by EuroBonus members. By August 2015, the EuroBonus program had in excess of four million members.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.sasgroup.net/en/sas-celebrates-four-million-eurobonus-members/ |title = SAS celebrates four million EuroBonus members |date= 21 August 2015 }} {{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Fly Home Club===\n''Fly Home Club'' was SAS's membership club for Scandinavians living in Spain. It has closed ever since economic conditions have worsened in Spain and as Scandinavians living in Spain have decided to return home or change locations.{{CN|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Hovercraft===\nBetween 1984 and 1994, SAS operated a [[hovercraft]] service between [[Malm\u00f6]] in Sweden and [[Copenhagen Airport]] in Denmark. Travellers could check in for their flights in Malm\u00f6 and the hovercraft were operated as connecting flights. The service was operated using a handful of [[British Hovercraft Corporation AP1-88]]s, which took an average journey time of 45 minutes to traverse the 17-mile route across the [[\u00d8resund]]; within its first year of operation, hovercraft reportedly carried roughly 100,000 passengers.<ref name = \"popmech hover\">{{cite web |url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=YOQDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA42&lpg=PA42 |title = New hovercraft replacing airliners |publisher = Popular Mechanics |date = March 1985 |volume = 162, No. 3 |page = 42 |issn = 0032-4558}}</ref> Due to the level of demand experienced, SAS examined the prospects for introducing larger hovercraft, capable of carrying up to 200 passengers, for the service.<ref name = \"popmech hover\"/> However, in 1994, the hovercraft were replaced by [[catamaran]]s. These vessels were in turn discontinued during 2000 due to the opening of the [[\u00d6resund bridge]], which provided a competing rail link between Malm\u00f6 and Copenhagen airport.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.classicfastferries.com/cff/pdf/cff_2004_1.pdf |title = SAS: The Hovering Years |publisher = Classic Fast Ferries |year = 2004}}</ref>\n\n===Wi-Fi===\nDuring May 2018, SAS launched a new high-speed [[WiFi]] system supplied by [[Viasat]]. The service is being rolled out on both the short and medium-haul fleets, it is expected to take two years to complete. The new system is much faster than previously available and will enable passengers to stream movies on board. Before this, SAS only offered WiFi on board on its long haul aircraft and a small number of Boeing 737s. WiFi is free for Eurobonus Gold and Diamond members as well as for those travelling in SAS Plus or Business. Otherwise, WiFi can be purchased with EuroBonus points or for a small fee.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sasgroup.net/en/sas-the-first-nordic-airline-to-launch-high-speed-wifi/ |title=SAS the first Nordic airline to launch high speed WiFi |website=SAS |accessdate=3 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n{{advert|date=February 2019}}\n* 2010:\n** Flightstats: Worlds Most Punctual Airline<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sasgroup.net/en/grand-slam-for-sas-at-grand-travel-awards/ |title=SAS nominated as both the world's and Europe's most punctual airline |publisher=sasgroup.net |date=17 January 2011 |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> \n** Simpliflying: Best Use of Social Media in a Crisis Situation<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/SAS/photos/a.281389815787.318771.140344030787/10150288373085788 SAS - Scandinavian Airlines on Facebook]. {{date|1-10-2010|dmy}}. Retrieved 25 January 2015.</ref>\n* 2011:\n** Edge Awards: Favourite Airline<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/SAS/photos/a.281389815787/10151523016235788/?type=1&theater |title=SAS - Scandinavian Airlines on Facebook |date=18 April 2012 |access-date=25 January 2015}}</ref>\n**  Grand Travel Award: Europe's Best Airline<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sasgroup.net/en/grand-slam-for-sas-at-grand-travel-awards/ |title=Grand slam for SAS at Grand Travel Awards |publisher=sasgroup.net |date={{date|17-02-2011|dmy}} |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref>\n** Webbie: Online Campaign of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sasgroup.net/en/sas-wins-online-campaign-of-the-year-award-2/ |title=SAS wins Online Campaign of the Year award |publisher=sasgroup.net |date=2011-02-11 |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref>\n* 2012:\n** Webbie Award: Online Campaign of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sasgroup.net/en/sas-wins-social-media-award-for-second-year-in-a-row/ |title=SAS wins social media award for second year in a row |publisher=sasgroup.net |date=2012-02-09 |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref>\n* 2013:\n** Freddie Awards: Best Customer Service in Europe/Africa<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/SAS/photos/a.281389815787.318771.140344030787/10152787060540788/ SAS - Scandinavian Airlines on Facebook]. {{date|29-4-2013}}. Retrieved 25 January 2015.</ref>\n** Sustainable Brand Index: Most Sustainable Airline<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/SAS/photos/a.281389815787.318771.140344030787/10152808409810788/ SAS - Scandinavian Airlines on Facebook]{{dead link|date=March 2019}}. {{date|5-7-2013|dmy}}. Retrieved 25 January 2015.</ref>\n* 2014:\n** Grand Travel Award: Europe's Best Airline<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travelnews.se/artiklar/nyheter/20140214/vinnarna-i-grand-travel-award-2014 |title=Vinnarna i Grand Travel Award 2014 |publisher=travelnews.se |date=2014-02-14 |accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref>\n* 2015:\n** Grand Travel Award: Europe's Best Airline<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boarding.no/art.asp?id=59155 |title=SAS k\u00e5ret til Europas beste flyselskap |publisher=boarding.no |date=2015-01-22 |accessdate=25 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403112734/http://www.boarding.no/art.asp?id=59155 |archivedate=3 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n** ServiceScore: Airline with highest service standards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tidningenharjedalen.se/jamtland/harjedalen/sykes-stor-del-i-sas-servicepris |title=Sykes stor del i SAS-servicepris |publisher=tidningenharjedalen.se |date=2015-04-30 |accessdate=2015-04-30}}</ref>\n\n==Incidents and accidents==\n{{main|List of Scandinavian Airlines accidents and incidents}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Aviation|Companies|Denmark|Norway|Sweden}}\n* [[SAS Group]]\n* [[Norwegian Aviation College]]\n* [[List of airports in Denmark]], [[List of airports in Norway|Norway]], and [[List of airports in Sweden|Sweden]]\n* [[List of the busiest airports in the Nordic countries]]\n* [[Transport in Denmark]], [[Transport in Norway|Norway]], and [[Transport in Sweden|Sweden]]\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{notelist}}\n\n;Citations\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons-inline|SAS Scandinavian Airlines}}\n;Company websites\n* [https://www.flysas.com/ SAS website] ( - )\n* [https://www.sas.dk/ SAS Denmark website]\n* [https://www.sas.no/ SAS Norway website]\n* [https://www.sas.se/ SAS Sweden website]\n* [https://www.sasgroup.net/ SAS Group corporate website]\n\n;Other websites\n* [http://www.viking256.se Viking Tails, Scandinavian airline history blog]\n* [http://www.airplanes.se/airlines.php?airline=Scandinavian%20Airlines Pictures of Scandinavian Airlines fleet]\n\n{{SAS Group}}\n{{Star Alliance}}\n{{Association of European Airlines}}\n{{IATA members|europe}}\n{{International Association of Aviation Personnel Schools}}\n{{Navbox Airlines of Denmark}}\n{{Navbox Airlines of Norway}}\n{{Navbox Airlines of Sweden}}\n\n[[Category:Scandinavian Airlines| ]]\n[[Category:Airlines of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Airlines of Norway]]\n[[Category:Airlines of Sweden]]\n[[Category:IATA members]]\n[[Category:SAS Group members]]\n[[Category:Association of European Airlines members]]\n[[Category:Airlines established in 1946]]\n[[Category:Danish brands]]\n[[Category:1946 establishments in Denmark]]\n[[Category:1946 establishments in Norway]]\n[[Category:1946 establishments in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Star Alliance]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Stockholm]]\n[[Category:Sigtuna Municipality]]\n", "name_user": "BD2412", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eJet era:Fixing links to disambiguation pages, improving links, other minor cleanup tasks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scandinavian_Airlines"}
